ce:section.ce:para:
World health organization (WHO) assign criteria in the term “ASSURED” to frame work point-of-care devices [53]. The device should be affordable, sensitive, specific, user-friendly, rapid and robust, equipment free and deliverable to end users. 
                           Affordable;
                         this paper device is cheap consuming reagents at reasonable prices. 
                           Sensitive;
                         potentiometric sensor provides the lowest detection limit (3.2 × 10−6 mol L−1) calculated at intersection between the calibration linear segment and the extrapolated arm of the background potential according to the IUPAC definition. Since the optical sensors need no special instrument for on-site applications, the visual detection limits are judged by the naked eye. KET is detected at 2.0 × 10−4 by fluorimetric versus 3.6 × 10−2 mol L−1 by colorimetric sensors corresponding to the distinguishable change from blank spot (Fig. 4B and C). 
                           Selectivity;
                         among the proposed sensing mechanisms, the color reaction is considered the most selective one. Although some interferences showed substantial potentiometric and fluorometric signals (Table 1), the combination of three detection mechanism poses the device in general as being specific. 
                           User-friendly;
                         sample is applied by less experienced individuals on a paper-device makes this design feasible to the end-user. The designed electrical connection with USB plug is convenient for potentiometric measurements asides from the handy use of cellular phone application for response optical detection. 
                           Rapid;
                         general detection methods are characterized by short analysis time. To put things into perspective, the fastest response was observed in case of colorimetric detection (instantaneous) followed by ion sensing membrane (20 s) then fluorescent sensor (1 min). 
                           Robust;
                         reagents stability on paper-based device was tested during a period of 30 days. Each day the same sample is applied to a new device. Devices are sealed in plastic sheets and stored at 25 ± 2 °C. Sealing process decreases the probability of PVC membrane hardening and decomposition of reagents. The electrodes are workable for 10 days with considerably stable potentials (RSD% = ±10.59; n = 10). The fairly stable reference electrode potentials and offset both impede the robustness of the test results. Fluorescent sensor is almost robust during the study period (RSD% = 7.74; n = 10), possibly due to a homogeneous distribution of sample in nanoprobe sensor. Results of potentiometric and fluorescent sensors in a 10 d period are displayed in Fig. 5B. Color detection zones remain stable and reactive to KET sample within 30 days. It is worth noting that homogeneity of formed color zones may be disrupted by formation of KET base needle crystals at high concentrations. This inter-sensor comparison also revealed for the good reproducibility of the production process as well as the stability of trimodal systems along examined period. 
                           Equipment free;
                         although simple proposed connections for potentiometric sensor, fluorescence detection needs readily available tools like cell phone and UV-torch and no equipment required for colour sensor. 
                           Deliverable;
                         This is a hand-held portable paper strip that is easily utilized and disposed. The developed KET-sensor is thus considered cheap and accurate with respect to other reported point-of-care devices. The proposed device is compared to reported and commercially available sensors with one detection mode (Table 2
                        ). Voltammetric sensor [15] provides lowest detection limit (1.0 × 10−9 mol L−1) among the reported KET sensors, however it suffers from of readily oxidizable interference in beverage. The reported color sensors were limited to drug substance [16,18] and water sample [17] while the commercial color kits could detect about 4.0 mg mL−1 of KET in beverages with appreciable sensitivity and specificity [54,55]. The proposed trimodal device outweighs other reported or commercially available kits as it provides good sensitivity with potentiometric detection enough for a date rape drug, improved sensitivity and feasibility with fluorescent sensor, and high selectivity.
